EventBridge: the event bus.

EventBridge is a serverless event bus that routes events to targets based on rules. Where S-N-S does pub/sub by subscription, EventBridge does routing by pattern match; the rule is the abstraction, not the subscription. There are three kinds of bus. The default event bus: every account has one, and AWS services automatically publish service events here, like E-C-2 state changes, S3 object events, CodePipeline transitions, and I-A-M activity, hundreds of event types. A custom event bus, for your own application's events, populated via put-events. And a partner event bus, where SaaS partners like Datadog, Stripe, and GitHub publish their events into a bus in your account. An event is a J-SON object with a small set of standard fields, source, detail-type, account, region, and time, plus a free-form detail payload, the same shape across A-W-S-service, SaaS, and custom events.

A rule has an event pattern that filters incoming events, with a rich syntax for exact values, lists, prefixes, numeric ranges, anything-but, and existence, and a list of up to five targets that matching events are delivered to. Targets can be almost anything: Lambda, Step Functions, S-Q-S, S-N-S, Kinesis, or another bus.

Three features show up in real architectures. Schema Registry auto-discovers the schema of events flowing through a bus and generates code bindings, in Python, Java, or TypeScript, so application code consumes typed objects instead of raw J-SON, useful as the event surface grows. EventBridge Pipes is a point-to-point integration, source to optional filter to optional enrichment to target, with no glue code; it replaces the very common "Lambda that polls one service and forwards to another" pattern, and the filter runs at the source. And Archive and Replay stores every event matching a pattern for a retention period and replays them back to a bus, for debugging or reprocessing after a bug fix. EventBridge also runs Scheduler, for cron and rate jobs.
